1) Appium: This is a free and open source automation testing tool which essentially replicates the native user interface by using Selenium web-driver. It’s a headless app, so your app doesn’t have to be running on the target device for the test to work. Additionally, it supports top mobile frameworks such as TestNG, Robotium, Android ESpresso, etc. The biggest downside (as with most things) comes down to cost of ownership. With a free option, support is limited to the user community. Appium also lacks the integrations more advanced automation platforms offer. For example, Selenium produced test automation is limited to parameters and data-driven capabilities.
2) Espresso: This framework is definitely useful and worth exploring, but is only available for Android. As an open source tool, it has more of the advanced obievious automation features, such as data and parameter driven tests. Also, it’s integrated within Android Studio, so operation is very simple for dev team users. All-in-all it’s not nearly as easy to access or use as many other testing tools, and isn’t available for Apps or the web.
